# 🌡️ LM35 Temperature Sensor

The **LM35** is a precision integrated-circuit temperature sensor manufactured by **Texas Instruments**. Unlike thermistors, the LM35 provides a **linear analog voltage output** that is directly proportional to the measured temperature, making it easy to interface with microcontrollers such as **Arduino**, **ESP32**, **STM32**, and **Raspberry Pi Pico**.

One of the biggest advantages of the LM35 is that its output is already calibrated in degrees Celsius, eliminating the need for complex calibration algorithms.

---

# Key Features

| Feature | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Sensor Type | Analog Temperature Sensor |
| Output Signal | Analog Voltage |
| Temperature Range | -55°C to +150°C |
| Accuracy | ±0.5°C (Typical at 25°C) |
| Operating Voltage | 4V – 30V |
| Output Scale | 10 mV/°C |
| Calibration | Factory Calibrated |
| Self-Heating | Very Low (Less than 0.1°C) |

---

# Pin Configuration

The LM35 has **three pins**.

```text
        _________
       |         |
       |  LM35   |
       |_________|
       | | | 
       | | |
      VCC OUT GND
```

| Pin | Name | Description |
|-----|------|-------------|
| 1 | VCC | Power Supply (4V–30V) |
| 2 | OUT | Analog Voltage Output |
| 3 | GND | Ground |

---

# Working Principle

The LM35 measures the ambient temperature and converts it into an analog voltage.

Its output increases **linearly** with temperature.

The relationship is:

```text
10 mV = 1°C
```

or

```text
Temperature (°C) = Output Voltage (mV) / 10
```

Example:

| Temperature | Output Voltage |
|-------------|----------------|
| 0°C | 0 mV |
| 25°C | 250 mV |
| 30°C | 300 mV |
| 50°C | 500 mV |
| 100°C | 1000 mV (1V) |

---

# How Arduino Reads the LM35

The Arduino's Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) converts the sensor's analog voltage into a digital value.

The conversion process is:

```text
LM35
   │
   ▼
Analog Voltage
   │
   ▼
Arduino ADC
   │
   ▼
Digital Value (0–1023)
   │
   ▼
Voltage Calculation
   │
   ▼
Temperature Calculation
```

---

# Temperature Calculation Formula

First, convert the ADC value into voltage.

```cpp
Voltage = (ADC_Value / 1024.0) × 5000
```

The voltage is calculated in **millivolts (mV)**.

Then convert voltage into temperature.

```cpp
Temperature = Voltage / 10
```

Example:

Suppose the Arduino reads:

```text
ADC = 205
```

Voltage:

```text
