# 💡 LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) with Arduino

An **LDR (Light Dependent Resistor)**, also known as a **photoresistor**, is an electronic component whose resistance changes according to the intensity of light falling on its surface.

When the surrounding environment becomes brighter, the resistance of the LDR decreases. In darker conditions, its resistance increases. This property makes the LDR an ideal sensor for applications involving light detection and automatic lighting systems.

---

# What is an LDR?

An LDR is a passive analog sensor that converts changes in light intensity into changes in electrical resistance.

Unlike digital sensors, an LDR does not directly produce digital values. Instead, it is commonly connected as part of a **voltage divider**, allowing a microcontroller such as an Arduino to measure the resulting analog voltage.

---

# Key Features

| Feature | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Sensor Type | Analog Light Sensor |
| Output | Analog Voltage |
| Operating Voltage | 3.3V – 5V (depends on the circuit) |
| Measurement | Light Intensity |
| Response Time | Moderate |
| Cost | Low |
| Interface | Analog Input |

---

# Working Principle

The resistance of an LDR changes depending on the amount of light.

```text
Bright Light
      ↓
Low Resistance
      ↓
Higher Output Voltage (Voltage Divider)
      ↓
Higher ADC Value

Darkness
      ↓
High Resistance
      ↓
Lower Output Voltage
      ↓
Lower ADC Value
```

> **Note:** Depending on how the voltage divider is wired, the output behavior may be reversed.

---

# Pin Connection

An LDR itself has only **two terminals** because it is simply a variable resistor.

A common Arduino circuit uses a **10kΩ resistor** to create a voltage divider.

```text
          5V
           │
          LDR
           │
           ├──────── A0
           │
         10kΩ
           │
          GND
```

---

# Arduino Wiring

| Component | Arduino Pin |
|------------|-------------|
| LDR | 5V |
| Junction (LDR + 10kΩ) | A0 |
| 10kΩ Resistor | GND |

---

# How Arduino Reads an LDR

The Arduino measures the analog voltage from the voltage divider.

```text
LDR
 │
 ▼
Voltage Divider
 │
 ▼
Analog Voltage
 │
 ▼
Arduino ADC
 │
 ▼
Digital Value (0–1023)
 │
 ▼
Serial Monitor
```

---

# Reading the Sensor

The analog input is read using:

```cpp
int lightValue = analogRead(A0);
```

The returned value ranges from:

```text
0 → 1023
```

Typical values:

| ADC Value | Light Level |
|-----------|-------------|
| 0–200 | Very Dark |
| 200–500 | Dim Light |
| 500–800 | Indoor Lighting |
| 800–1023 | Bright Light |

These ranges may vary depending on the specific LDR and resistor used.

